SENATE BILL 108
M3 6lr0067
(PRE–FILED) CF HB 250
By: Chair, Education, Energy, and the Environment Committee (By Request –
Departmental – Environment)
Requested: September 25, 2025
Introduced and read first time: January 14, 2026
Assigned to: Education, Energy, and the Environment
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Committee amendments withdrawn, February 20, 2026
Senate action: Adopted with substitute committee amendments, February 21, 2026, and
floor amendments
Read second time: February 23, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Environment – Water Resources and Wetlands – Enforcement
3 FOR the purpose of authorizing the Department of the Environment to impose an
4 administrative penalty for certain violations related to the appropriation or use of
5 water and dam safety; repealing a certain limitation on the Department’s authority
6 to issue certain orders and send certain notices related to dam safety; authorizing
7 the Department to impose an administrative penalty for certain violations related to
8 wetlands construction, modification, or development; requiring the Department to
9 take certain actions before imposing certain civil or administrative penalties;
10 requiring certain administrative penalties to be paid into the Maryland Clean Water
11 Fund; and generally relating to the enforcement authority of the Department of the
12 Environment.
13 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
14 Article – Environment
15 Section 5–514 through 5–516
16 Annotated Code of Maryland
17 (2013 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
18 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
19 Article – Environment
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0108*

2 SENATE BILL 108
1 Section 9–320(a) and (c)
2 Annotated Code of Maryland
3 (2014 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
4 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
5 Article – Environment
6 Section 9–320(b) and 16–502
7 Annotated Code of Maryland
8 (2014 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
9 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
10 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
11 Article – Environment
12 5–514.
13 (a) (1) In addition to being subject to an injunctive action under this subtitle,
14 a person who violates any provision of this subtitle or any regulation, order, or permit
15 adopted or issued under this subtitle is liable for a civil penalty not exceeding $10,000 per
16 violation to be collected in a civil action brought by the Department.
17 (2) Each day a violation occurs or continues is a separate violation under
18 this subsection.
19 (3) (i) Before bringing a civil action against a local government under
20 this subsection, the Department shall meet and consult with the local government to seek
21 an alternative resolution to the contested issue.
22 (ii) Prior consultation by the Department with the local government
23 shall constitute compliance with this subsection.
24 (b) A person who violates a provision of this subtitle or a regulation adopted under
25 this subtitle is subject to the penalties provided in § 9–343 of this article.
26 (C) (1) IN ADDITION TO ANY OTHER REMEDIES AVAILABLE AT LAW OR IN
27 EQUITY AND AFTER AN OPPORTUNITY FOR A HEARING, WHICH MAY BE WAIVED IN
28 WRITING BY THE PERSON ACCUSED OF A VIOLATION, THE DEPARTMENT MAY
29 IMPOSE A PENALTY FOR VIOLATION OF ANY PROVISION OF THIS SUBTITLE OR ANY
30 REGULATION, ORDER, OR PERMIT ADOPTED OR ISSUED UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.
31 (2) THE PENALTY IMPOSED ON A PERSON UNDER THIS SUBSECTION
32 SHALL BE:
33 (I) UP TO $5,000 FOR EACH VIOLATION, BUT NOT EXCEEDING
34 $100,000 TOTAL; AND

SENATE BILL 108 3
1 (II) ASSESSED WITH CONSIDERATION GIVEN TO:
2 1. THE WILLFULNESS OF THE VIOLATION, THE EXTENT
3 TO WHICH THE EXISTENCE OF THE VIOLATION WAS KNOWN TO BUT UNCORRECTED
4 BY THE VIOLATOR, AND THE EXTENT TO WHICH THE VIOLATOR EXERCISED
5 REASONABLE CARE;
6 2. ANY ACTUAL HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR TO
7 HUMAN HEALTH, INCLUDING INJURY TO OR IMPAIRMENT OF THE USE OF THE
8 WATERS OF THE STATE OR THE NATURAL RESOURCES OF THE STATE;
9 3. THE COST OF CLEANUP AND THE COST OF
10 RESTORATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES;
11 4. THE NATURE AND DEGREE OF INJURY TO OR
12 INTERFERENCE WITH GENERAL WELFARE, HEALTH, AND PROPERTY;
13 5. THE EXTENT TO WHICH THE LOCATION OF THE
14 VIOLATION, INCLUDING LOCATION NEAR WATERS OF THE STATE OR AREAS OF
15 HUMAN POPULATION, CREATES THE POTENTIAL FOR HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT
16 OR TO HUMAN HEALTH OR SAFETY;
17 6. THE AVAILABLE TECHNOLOGY AND ECONOMIC
18 REASONABLENESS OF CONTROLLING, REDUCING, OR ELIMINATING THE VIOLATION;
19 7. THE DEGREE OF HAZARD OR HARM POSED BY THE
20 VIOLATION; AND
21 8. THE EXTENT TO WHICH THE CURRENT VIOLATION IS
22 PART OF A RECURRENT PATTERN OF THE SAME OR SIMILAR TYPE OF VIOLATION
23 COMMITTED BY THE VIOLATOR; AND
24 9. THE DEGREE OF COOPERATION WITH THE
25 DEPARTMENT AFTER BEING NOTIFIED OF THE VIOLATION AND ANY GOOD FAITH
26 EFFORTS TO ADDRESS THE VIOLATION.
27 (3) EACH DAY A VIOLATION EXISTS IS A SEPARATE VIOLATION UNDER
28 THIS SUBSECTION.
29 (4) ANY PENALTY IMPOSED UNDER THIS SUBSECTION IS PAYABLE TO
30 THE STATE AND COLLECTIBLE IN ANY MANNER PROVIDED AT LAW FOR THE
31 COLLECTION OF DEBTS.

4 SENATE BILL 108
1 (5) IF ANY PERSON WHO IS LIABLE TO PAY A PENALTY IMPOSED
2 UNDER THIS SUBSECTION FAILS TO PAY THE PENALTY AFTER DEMAND, THE
3 AMOUNT, TOGETHER WITH INTEREST AND ANY COSTS THAT MAY ACCRUE, SHALL BE
4 A LIEN IN FAVOR OF THE STATE ON ANY:
5 (I) REAL PROPERTY OF THE PERSON WHEN RECORDED WITH
6 THE CLERK OF THE CIRCUIT COURT FOR THE COUNTY IN WHICH THE PROPERTY IS
7 LOCATED; AND
8 (II) PERSONAL PROPERTY OF THE PERSON WHEN ATTACHED
9 AND LEVIED BY THE STATE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE MARYLAND RULES.
10 (D) BEFORE TAKING ANY CIVIL OR ADMINISTRATIVE ACTION TO RECOVER A
11 PENALTY UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OR (C) OF THIS SECTION, THE DEPARTMENT
12 SHALL:
13 (1) PROVIDE THE PERSON ALLEGED TO HAVE VIOLATED THIS
14 SUBTITLE WITH WRITTEN NOTICE OF THE PROPOSED PENALTY AND AN
15 OPPORTUNITY FOR AN INFORMAL MEETING CONCERNING SETTLEMENT OF THE
16 PROPOSED CIVIL OR ADMINISTRATIVE PENALTY;
17 (2) USE DISCRETION TO DETERMINE WHETHER A FORMAL
18 ENFORCEMENT ACTION UNDER THIS SECTION IS APPROPRIATE; AND
19 (3) IF APPLICABLE, REVIEW ANY GOOD FAITH APPLICATION FROM
20 THE PERSON, OR AN AUTHORIZED REPRESENTATIVE OF THE PERSON, FOR A LOAN
21 FROM THE PRIVATE DAM REPAIR FUND.
22 [(c)] (D) (E) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, all funds
23 collected by the Department under this section, including any civil [penalty] OR
24 ADMINISTRATIVE PENALTIES or any fine imposed by a court under the provisions of this
25 section, shall be paid into the Maryland Clean Water Fund.
26 (2) Funds collected by the Department under this section relating to an
27 unsafe condition shall be paid into the Private Dam Repair Fund.
28 5–515.
29 (a) After or concurrently with the service of a complaint under this subtitle
30 [relating to water appropriation and use], the Department may:
31 (1) Issue an order that requires the person to whom the order is directed to
32 take corrective action within a time set in the order;

SENATE BILL 108 5
1 (2) Send a written notice that requires the person to whom the notice is
2 directed to file a written report about the alleged violation; or
3 (3) Send a written notice that requires the person to whom the notice is
4 directed:
5 (i) To appear at a hearing before the Department at a time and place
6 the Department sets to answer the charges in the complaint; or
7 (ii) To file a written report and also to appear at a hearing before the
8 Department at a time and place the Department sets to answer the charges in the
9 complaint.
10 (b) Any order issued under this section is effective immediately, according to its
11 terms, when it is served.
12 5–516.
13 (a) The Department shall give notice and hold any hearing related to orders
14 imposed under [the water appropriation and use provisions of] this subtitle in accordance
15 with the Administrative Procedure Act.
16 (b) (1) Within 10 days after being served with an order under § 5–515(a)(1) of
17 this subtitle, the person served may request in writing a hearing before the Department.
18 (2) (i) Subject to subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph, if a request for a
19 hearing on an order is made under this subsection, the Department shall:
20 1. Hold the hearing promptly after receiving the request; and
21 2. Render a decision promptly after the hearing.
22 (ii) If a request for a hearing on an order is made under this
23 subsection and the Department alleges in the order that there is an imminent threat or
24 danger to the public health or safety or to the environment, the Department shall:
25 1. Hold the hearing within 10 days after receiving the
26 request; and
27 2. Render a decision within 10 days after the hearing.
28 (c) Within 10 days after being served with a notice under § 5–515(a)(2) of this
29 subtitle, the person served may request in writing a hearing before the Department.
30 (d) The Department may make a verbatim record of the proceedings of any
31 hearing held under this subtitle.

6 SENATE BILL 108
1 (e) (1) In connection with any hearing under this subtitle, the Department
2 may:
3 (i) Subpoena any person or evidence; and
4 (ii) Order a witness to give evidence.
5 (2) A subpoenaed witness shall receive the same fees and mileage
6 reimbursement as if the hearing were part of a civil action.
7 (3) If a person fails to comply with a subpoena or order issued under this
8 subsection, on petition of the Department, a circuit court, by order, may:
9 (i) Compel obedience to the Department’s order or subpoena; or
10 (ii) Compel testimony or the production of evidence.
11 (4) The court may punish as contempt any failure to obey its order issued
12 under this section.
13 9–320.
14 (a) There is a Maryland Clean Water Fund.
15 (b) Except as provided in § 9–303.4 of this subtitle, the following payments shall
16 be made into the Maryland Clean Water Fund:
17 (1) All application fees, permit fees, renewal fees, and funds collected by
18 the Department under this subtitle, including any civil or administrative penalty or any
19 fine imposed by a court under the provisions of this subtitle;
20 (2) [Any] WITH THE EXCEPTION OF PENALTIES AND FINES REQUIRED
21 TO BE PAID INTO THE PRIVATE DAM REPAIR FUND, ANY civil OR ADMINISTRATIVE
22 penalty or any fine imposed by a court under the provisions of Title 5, Subtitle 5 of this
23 article [relating to water appropriation and use];
24 (3) Any civil or administrative penalty or any fine imposed by a court under
25 the provisions of Title 4, Subtitle 1 of this article;
26 (4) Any fees or funds that the Department collects under Subtitle 2, Part
27 III of this title and §§ 9–269 and 9–270 of this title and any civil or administrative penalty
28 or fine imposed by a court under the provisions of Subtitle 2 of this title;
29 (5) Any fees or funds that the Department collects under Subtitle 24 of this
30 title and any civil or administrative penalty or fine imposed by a court under the provisions
31 of Subtitle 24 of this title; and

SENATE BILL 108 7
1 (6) Any other fees legally authorized to be paid into the Maryland Clean
2 Water Fund.
3 (c) The Department shall use the Maryland Clean Water Fund for activities that
4 are related to:
5 (1) The identification, monitoring, and regulation of the proper discharge
6 of effluent into the waters of the State including program development of these activities
7 as provided by the State budget;
8 (2) The management, conservation, protection, and preservation of the
9 State’s groundwater and surface water including program development of these activities
10 as provided by the State budget;
11 (3) Correcting to the extent possible the failure to implement or maintain
12 erosion and sediment controls;
13 (4) Administration of the sediment control program;
14 (5) Emergency removal of sewage sludge or mitigation of the effect of any
15 utilization of sewage sludge that the Department finds:
16 (i) Endangers public health, safety, or welfare; or
17 (ii) Endangers or damages natural resources;
18 (6) Activities that are:
19 (i) Conducted by the Department, by a local health official, or by the
20 local health official’s designee under § 9–243(e) of this title;
21 (ii) Related to identifying, monitoring, or regulating the utilization
22 of sewage sludge, including program development; and
23 (iii) Conducted by the Department under Subtitle 24 of this title; and
24 (7) Providing supplemental inspections and monitoring of sewage sludge
25 utilization sites by:
26 (i) Contracting with a county on request of that county to provide
27 supplemental inspections and monitoring; and
28 (ii) Limiting the value of services provided under the contract to no
29 more than 45% of the generator fees for sludge utilized in that county that is generated
30 outside of that county or service area.
31 16–502.

8 SENATE BILL 108
1 (a) (1) A person who violates any provision of this title or any regulation,
2 permit, license, or order issued under this title shall be liable for a penalty not exceeding
3 $10,000, which may be recovered in a civil action.
4 (2) In imposing a penalty under this subsection, the court may consider the
5 factors in § 9–342(b)(2)(ii) of this article and any other relevant factors.
6 (3) EACH DAY A VIOLATION EXISTS IS A SEPARATE VIOLATION UNDER
7 THIS SUBSECTION.
8 (b) The circuit court may issue an injunction requiring the person to cease the
9 violation and restore the area unlawfully dredged or filled.
10 (c) Before taking any civil action to recover a penalty under subsection (a) of this
11 section, the Department shall provide the person alleged to have violated this title with
12 written notice of the proposed penalty and an opportunity for an informal meeting
13 concerning settlement of the proposed civil action.
14 (D) (1) IN ADDITION TO ANY OTHER REMEDIES AVAILABLE AT LAW OR IN
15 EQUITY AND AFTER AN OPPORTUNITY FOR A HEARING, WHICH MAY BE WAIVED IN
16 WRITING BY THE PERSON ACCUSED OF A VIOLATION, THE DEPARTMENT MAY
17 IMPOSE A PENALTY FOR VIOLATION OF ANY PROVISION OF THIS TITLE OR ANY
18 REGULATION, ORDER, OR PERMIT ADOPTED OR ISSUED UNDER THIS TITLE.
19 (2) THE PENALTY IMPOSED ON A PERSON UNDER THIS SUBSECTION
20 SHALL BE:
21 (I) UP TO $5,000 FOR EACH VIOLATION, BUT NOT EXCEEDING
22 $100,000 TOTAL; AND
23 (II) ASSESSED WITH CONSIDERATION GIVEN TO:
24 1. THE WILLFULNESS OF THE VIOLATION, THE EXTENT
25 TO WHICH THE EXISTENCE OF THE VIOLATION WAS KNOWN TO BUT UNCORRECTED
26 BY THE VIOLATOR, AND THE EXTENT TO WHICH THE VIOLATOR EXERCISED
27 REASONABLE CARE;
28 2. ANY ACTUAL HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR TO
29 HUMAN HEALTH, INCLUDING INJURY TO OR IMPAIRMENT OF THE USE OF THE
30 WATERS OF THE STATE OR THE NATURAL RESOURCES OF THE STATE;
31 3. THE COST OF CLEANUP AND THE COST OF
32 RESTORATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES;

SENATE BILL 108 9
1 4. THE NATURE AND DEGREE OF INJURY TO OR
2 INTERFERENCE WITH GENERAL WELFARE, HEALTH, AND PROPERTY;
3 5. THE EXTENT TO WHICH THE LOCATION OF THE
4 VIOLATION, INCLUDING LOCATION NEAR WATERS OF THE STATE OR AREAS OF
5 HUMAN POPULATION, CREATES THE POTENTIAL FOR HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT
6 OR TO HUMAN HEALTH OR SAFETY;
7 6. THE AVAILABLE TECHNOLOGY AND ECONOMIC
8 REASONABLENESS OF CONTROLLING, REDUCING, OR ELIMINATING THE VIOLATION;
9 7. THE DEGREE OF HAZARD POSED BY THE PARTICULAR
10 POLLUTANT OR POLLUTANTS INVOLVED; AND
11 8. THE EXTENT TO WHICH THE CURRENT VIOLATION IS
12 PART OF A RECURRENT PATTERN OF THE SAME OR SIMILAR TYPE OF VIOLATION
13 COMMITTED BY THE VIOLATOR; AND
14 9. THE DEGREE OF COOPERATION WITH THE
15 DEPARTMENT AFTER BEING NOTIFIED OF THE VIOLATION AND ANY GOOD FAITH
16 EFFORTS TO ADDRESS THE VIOLATION.
17 (3) EACH DAY A VIOLATION EXISTS IS A SEPARATE VIOLATION UNDER
18 THIS SUBSECTION.
19 (4) ANY PENALTY IMPOSED UNDER THIS SUBSECTION IS PAYABLE TO
20 THE STATE AND COLLECTIBLE IN ANY MANNER PROVIDED AT LAW FOR THE
21 COLLECTION OF DEBTS.
22 (5) IF ANY PERSON WHO IS LIABLE TO PAY A PENALTY IMPOSED
23 UNDER THIS SUBSECTION FAILS TO PAY THE PENALTY AFTER DEMAND, THE
24 AMOUNT, TOGETHER WITH INTEREST AND ANY COSTS THAT MAY ACCRUE, SHALL BE
25 A LIEN IN FAVOR OF THE STATE ON ANY:
26 (I) REAL PROPERTY OF THE PERSON WHEN RECORDED WITH
27 THE CLERK OF THE CIRCUIT COURT FOR THE COUNTY IN WHICH THE PROPERTY IS
28 LOCATED; AND
29 (II) PERSONAL PROPERTY OF THE PERSON WHEN ATTACHED
30 AND LEVIED BY THE STATE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE MARYLAND RULES.
31 (D) Before taking any civil OR ADMINISTRATIVE action to recover a penalty
32 under subsection (a) OR (C) of this section, the Department shall:

10 SENATE BILL 108
1 (1) [provide] PROVIDE the person alleged to have violated this title with
2 written notice of the proposed penalty and an opportunity for an informal meeting
3 concerning settlement of the proposed civil OR ADMINISTRATIVE action; AND
4 (2) USE DISCRETION TO DETERMINE WHETHER A FORMAL
5 ENFORCEMENT ACTION UNDER THIS SECTION IS APPROPRIATE.
6 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, if any provision of this Act or
7 the application of any provision of this Act to any person or circumstance is held invalid for
8 any reason in a court of competent jurisdiction, the invalidity does not affect other
9 provisions or any other application of this Act that can be given effect without the invalid
10 provision or application, and for this purpose the provisions of this Act are declared
11 severable.
12 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
13 July 1, 2026.
